\begin_layout Standard
You may have heard the claim 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

there's no such thing as subtraction—it's just adding the opposite
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or something like it.
 There is a vital concept of linear algebra buried in this addage.
 The link between addition, opposites, and zero that makes subtraction optional
 is a well known property of real numbers.
 The sum of opposites is zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why zero, and not some other number? Zero is that special number that can
 be added to any number without changing its value.
 There is no other! In symbols, 
\begin_inset Formula $a+0=0+a=a$
\end_inset

.
 This property is so special it has a name.
 Zero is the 
\series bold
additive identity
\series default
 for real numbers—the word 
\shape italic
identity
\shape default
 to signal this special property and the word 
\shape italic
additive
\shape default
 to document the operation.
 The additive inverse, or opposite, of a real number 
\series bold
\shape italic
is defined
\series default
\shape default
 by the fact that adding the two yields the additive identity.
 Two numbers are additive inverses (opposites) if and only if their sum
 is the additive identity (zero).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Likewise, one is that special number that can be multiplied by any number
 without changing its value.
 Consequently, one is the 
\series bold
multiplicative identity
\series default
 for real numbers.
 In symbols, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\cdot1=1\cdot a=a$
\end_inset

.
 The multiplicative inverse (reciprocal) of a real number 
\series bold
\shape italic
is defined
\series default
\shape default
 by the fact that multiplying the two yields the multiplicative identity.
 Two numbers are multiplicative inverses (reciprocals) if and only if their
 product is the multiplicative identity (one).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The link between multiplication, reciprocals, and one is analogous to the
 link between addition, opposites, and zero.
 For any real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are reciprocals if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle a\cdot b=b\cdot a=1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are opposites if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle a+b=b+a=0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The same relationship holds among addition, opposites, and zero as holds
 among multiplication, reciprocals, and one.
 Addition and multiplication are operations, opposites and reciprocals are
 inverses, and zero and one are identities.
\end_layout

